<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="191" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d191">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72115/3363</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Swiss Chargé</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HCP1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hübscher</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <p>The Secretary of State presents his compliments to the Chargé d’Affaires
                                <hi rend="italic">ad interim</hi> of Switzerland, in charge of
                            German interests in the United States and, with reference to the
                            latter’s note of June 25, 1918,<note n="1" xml:id="d191fn1">Not
                                printed.</note> in which inquiry was made whether alien enemies
                            interned in the United States are permitted to send money to Germany,
                            has the honor to state that it is not deemed advisable at the present
                            time to extend this privilege to the class of interned German nationals
                            referred to.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <dateline rendition="#left">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                                </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-09"><hi rend="italic">August 9, 1918</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>